"De Jesus Jr. W.C., Valadares Jr. R., Cecílio R.A., Moraes W.B., Do Vale F.X.R., Alves F.R., Paul P.A.","Worldwide geographical distribution of Black Sigatoka for banana: Predictions based on climate change models",2008,"Scientia Agricola","65","SPEC. ISS.",,"40","53",,,10.1590/S0103-90162008000700008,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-62149141705&partnerID=40&md5=aceb3baee9295def5038ca715bb9627d","UFES/CCA, Depto. de Produção Vegetal, Alto Universitário, s/n., C.P. 16, 29500-000 - Alegre, ES, Brazil; UFV/CCA, Depto. de Fitopatologia, 36570-000 - Viçosa, MG, Brazil; Ohio State University, Dept. of Plant Pathology, Wooster, OH, United States","De Jesus Jr., W.C., UFES/CCA, Depto. de Produção Vegetal, Alto Universitário, s/n., C.P. 16, 29500-000 - Alegre, ES, Brazil; Valadares Jr., R., UFES/CCA, Depto. de Produção Vegetal, Alto Universitário, s/n., C.P. 16, 29500-000 - Alegre, ES, Brazil; Cecílio, R.A., UFES/CCA, Depto. de Produção Vegetal, Alto Universitário, s/n., C.P. 16, 29500-000 - Alegre, ES, Brazil; Moraes, W.B., UFES/CCA, Depto. de Produção Vegetal, Alto Universitário, s/n., C.P. 16, 29500-000 - Alegre, ES, Brazil; Do Vale, F.X.R., UFV/CCA, Depto. de Fitopatologia, 36570-000 - Viçosa, MG, Brazil; Alves, F.R., UFES/CCA, Depto. de Produção Vegetal, Alto Universitário, s/n., C.P. 16, 29500-000 - Alegre, ES, Brazil; Paul, P.A., Ohio State University, Dept. of Plant Pathology, Wooster, OH, United States","Global climatic changes will potentially influence plant diseases and the efficacy of their management options. One of the most likely impacts of climate change will be felt by the geographical distribution of plant diseases. Black Sigatoka is considered the most damaging and costly disease of banana. The socio-economic impact of this disease has continued to increase as the pathogen reaches new areas and the disease becomes more difficult to be controled. The objectives of this research were to compare the global geographical distribution of the disease based on maps elaborated using weather data representing: i) current and future periods (2020, 2050 and 2080), ii) Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change scenarios A2 and B2, iii) predictions based on six different climate change models and the ""multimodel ensemble"" and, iv) individual months. The ""multimodel ensemble"" lead to a reduction in the variability of the simulations when compared to the results obtained using the individual models separately. The predictions suggested that, in the future, areas favorable for the development of the Black Sigatoka disease will decrease. This reduction will occur gradually and will be higher for the A2 than for the B2 scenario. Changes in the geographical distribution of the disease will occur from one month to another, with unfavorable areas becoming favorable and vice-versa. However, in spite of these changes, extensive areas will still continue to be favorable for the occurrence of Black Sigatoka.","Global climate change; Musa spp.; Mycosphaerella fijiensis","Musa; Mycosphaerella fijiensis",,,,,,"BERGOT, M., CLOPPET, E., PÉRARNAUD, V., DÉQUÉ, M., MARÇAIS, B., DESPREZ-LOUSTAU, M.L., Simulation of potential range expansion of oak disease caused by Phytophthora cinnamomi under climate change (2004) Global Change Biology, 10, pp. 1539-1552; BOAG, B., CRAWFORD, J.W., NEILSON, R., The effect of potential climatic changes on the geographical distribution of the plant-parasitic nematodes Xiphinema and Longidorus in Europe (1991) Nematologica, 37, pp. 312-323; BOURGEOIS, G., BOURQUE, A., DEAUDELIN, G., Modelling the impact of climate change on disease incidence: A bioclimatic challenge (2004) Canadian Journal of Plant Pathology, 26, pp. 284-290; BRASIER, C.M., DREYER, E., AUSSENAC, G., Phytophthora cinnamomi and oak decline in southern Europe. Environmental constraints including climate change (1996) Annales des Sciences Forestieres, 53, pp. 347-358; BRASIER, C.M., SCOTT, J.K., European oak declines and global warmin